Forecasting New Policy Counts using the MMM ETS model

Brittany Fuzia

3/14/19

This project aims to fit the smoothing parameters for the ETS model with Bayesian methods

The parameters are used to forecast the time series

Load New Policy Count (npc) data

dnpc <- read.csv("New Policy Count.csv", sep = "\t")
dnpc <- dnpc[,1:3] #only keep number, date, and new policy count
names(dnpc) <- c("t", "date", "y") #name cols
dnpc <- subset(dnpc, !is.na(y)) #get rid of nans (missing data for most recent months which only have forecasted values)
dnpc$y <-  dnpc$y/1e3 #change units to thousands of policy counts
dnpc$date <- as.Date(dnpc$date, '%m/%d/%Y')
yts <- ts(dnpc$y, start=c(2011,1), frequency=12) #turn into time series class
dygraph(yts) #plot data

Calculate starting points for the initial states

m <- 12 #number of periods per season
N <- nrow(dnpc) #how many data points
Ns <- as.integer(N/m) #how many seasons

# get yearly avg
savg <- vector()
for (j in 1:Ns) {
  savgsum <- 0.
  scount <- 0
  for (k in (m*(j-1)+1):(m*j)) {
    if (k<=N){
      savgsum <- savgsum + yts[k] 
      scount <- scount + 1
    }
  }
  savg[j] <- savgsum/scount
}

# initial seasonality == s0
# get avg ratio from average for each period
s0 <- vector()
for (i in 1:m) {
  value <-  0
  vcount <-  0
  for (j in 1:Ns) {
    if ((m*(j-1)+i)<=N) {
      value <- value + yts[m*(j-1)+i]/savg[j]
      vcount <- vcount + 1
    }
  }
  s0[i] <-  value/vcount
}
s0 <- s0/(sum(s0)/12) #normalize so sum(seasonality)==number of periods==12

yts_s1adj <-  ts(yts[1:12]/s0, start=c(2011,1), frequency=12)

# get l0 and b0 from linear regression of first 10 data points
x <- 1:10
initreg <- lm(yts_s1adj[x]~x)
l0 <- summary(initreg)$coefficients['(Intercept)','Estimate'] #==initial level
b0 <- 1+summary(initreg)$coefficients['x','Estimate']/summary(initreg)$coefficients['(Intercept)','Estimate'] #==initial trend

Fit MMM model w/ stan

The MMM model is a multiplicative model which includes a level, trend, and seasonality

The smoothed and forecasted values are level*trend*seasonality*(1+noise)

# Stan requires a list of the parameters that I give it in the 'data' section of the stan file: npc_MMM.stan
## y=the data, N=# of data pts, m=# of periods per season, Ns=#seasons
### init_prior is where I specificy the means of the prior distributions for the initial states (these are the values I calculated earlier)
#### prior_width is used to define the std dev of the prior distributions, right now it's written so std dev[i]=prior_width*init_prior[i]
standata <- list(y=yts,N=N,m=m,Ns=Ns,init_prior=c(l0,b0,s0),prior_width=0.1)

# To run stan, you need to give it the file with the model, the data, tell it how many steps you want to use to 'warmup' or 'burn in' the distributions
## and how many steps you want the walkers to take in total
### The standard number of chains is 4, but that can be specified with chains=#
rstanfit <- stan(file='npc_MMM.stan',data=standata,warmup=500,iter=5000)

Look at the resulting fit parameters, and check for convergence

For the MMM model, the parameters are: the smoothing parameters alpha (level), beta (trend), gamma (seasonality), and sigma (the amount of random noise)

First, look at the traces, which are just every point sampled by stan for each of the four chains

You can see where the distribution is burnt in and the walkers are sampling the distributions

# Traces for the smoothing params and noise
plot(rstanfit, plotfun='trace', pars = c('alpha','beta','gamma','sigma'), inc_warmup=TRUE)

# Traces for the initial states
plot(rstanfit,plotfun='trace',pars=c('l0','b0','s0'),inc_warmup=TRUE)

Second, look at parameter contours to visualize the distributions

# Dists for smoothing params
pairs(rstanfit, pars=c('alpha','beta','gamma','sigma'))

# Dists for initial states
pairs(rstanfit,pars=c('l0','b0','s0'))

A summary of the distributions

stansum <- summary(rstanfit)$summary #gives statistics on all of the fit parameters
chains <- extract(rstanfit) #extracts the chains for the walkers

print(c(mean(chains$alpha), mean(chains$beta), mean(chains$gamma))) #mean not really a good summary for beta/gamma
## [1] 0.72189254 0.04210418 0.07619285

Check out the states from the fit

level_fit <- apply(chains$l,2,mean) #get the mean for each column (which is each time step)
trend_fit <- apply(chains$b,2,mean)
seasonality_fit <- apply(chains$s,2,mean)

plot(dnpc$t, level_fit, type='l') #visualize

plot(dnpc$t, trend_fit, type='l')

plot(dnpc$t, seasonality_fit, type='l')
